I am wondering how many of the @Wework pundits have looked at the company's financials.... I think we know the answer.
Nope. Rather why are market dialogues typically one sided and in the case now why aren’t the negatives aired at all?

thanks but I wasn't addressing market timing nor trading. I was addressing an imbalanced view, the absence of a discussion of negatives (as if they didn't even exist) in formulating an intermediate term investment view or commentary that exists today in the financial media, rev.

those concerns i expressed may very well be offset by the positives - but in having no discourse about those headwinds is silly especially in a world in which so many outcomes are possible and unusual conditions exist (e.g. neg interest rates on $17 trill of sov debt).
Why is respectful debate usually considered disrespectful?

Or how about The Fed Pushing on a String and the consequences of $17 trillion of negative yielding sovereign debt. Passing over the concerns - as was done with the different concerns in 2007 - is probably an unwise decision.

"Group stink"? There is never or hardly any discussion of headwinds. There seems to be a near unanimity that the market rips higher on a trade agreement and that liquidity is the driving force for stocks. Untenable debt loads around the world, wealth/income imbalances,

a record lack or coordination and cooperation between the world's major trading partners, an earnings recession, manufacturing weakness seeping into services, political and geopolitical instability, an extreme level of partisanship (eliminating possibility of fiscal initiatives)

a rising US dollar adversely impacting S&P profitability, risks associated with a changing market structure, souring Chinese/EU economies and a rally in 2019 soely based on pe expansion. @cnbcfastmoney @SquawkCNBC @tomkeene @terranovajoe @ScottWapnerCNBC
